{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608219","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608219"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:30:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:30:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15989"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15989","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15989"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8680"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114794"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8680","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8680"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15989"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96797"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8606"},{"type":"tags","id":"8669"},{"type":"tags","id":"8693"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20776"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20779"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114794","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114794"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring early embryonic development, mesoderm differentiates into three main regions: paraxial mesoderm, intermediate mesoderm, and lateral plate mesoderm. Each region gives rise to specific structures in the developing embryo.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures develops primarily from paraxial mesoderm?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Axial skeleton","Blood vessels and heart","Kidneys and gonads","Limb bones and girdles","Smooth muscle of gut"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eaxial skeleton\u003C/strong\u003E develops from paraxial mesoderm, which segments to form somites. These somites differentiate into sclerotome (forming vertebrae and ribs), myotome (forming skeletal muscle), and dermatome (forming dermis of the back).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood vessels and heart\u003C/strong\u003E develop from lateral plate mesoderm, whilst \u003Cstrong\u003Ekidneys and gonads\u003C/strong\u003E develop from intermediate mesoderm. \u003Cstrong\u003ELimb bones and girdles\u003C/strong\u003E (appendicular skeleton) develop from lateral plate mesoderm, and \u003Cstrong\u003Esmooth muscle of gut\u003C/strong\u003E develops from splanchnic layer of lateral plate mesoderm. Understanding the derivatives of different mesodermal regions is crucial for comprehending normal embryonic development and potential developmental abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Paraxial mesoderm forms somites which give rise to the axial skeleton, skeletal muscle, and dermis of the back.","Different types of mesoderm (paraxial, intermediate, lateral plate) form distinct embryonic structures."],"references":["Ferretti E, Hadjantonakis AK. Mesoderm specification and diversification: from single cells to emergent tissues. Curr Opin Cell Biol. 2019 Dec;61:110-116. doi: 10.1016/j.ceb.2019.07.012. Epub 2019 Aug 30. PMID: 31476530; PMCID: PMC6910985","Gaillard R, Steegers EA, de Jongste JC, Hofman A, Jaddoe VW. Tracking of fetal growth characteristics during different trimesters and the risks of adverse birth outcomes. Int J Epidemiol. 2014 Aug;43(4):1140-53. doi: 10.1093/ije/dyu036. Epub 2014 Mar 5. PMID: 24603318; PMCID: PMC4258770","Chen X, Liu H, Li Y, Zhang W, Zhou A, Xia W, Xu S. First-trimester fetal size, accelerated growth in utero, and child neurodevelopment in a cohort study. BMC Med. 2024 Apr 29;22(1):181. doi: 10.1186/s12916-024-03390-3. PMID: 38685041; PMCID: PMC11059611","Godfrey KM, Inskip HM, Hanson MA. The long-term effects of prenatal development on growth and metabolism. Semin Reprod Med. 2011 May;29(3):257-65. doi: 10.1055/s-0031-1275518. Epub 2011 Jul 18. PMID: 21769765; PMCID: PMC3685133","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96797"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15989"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96797","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96797"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-20T11:52:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-20T11:52:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8680"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114794"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading